SIMPLE: repay
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Repay
<hw>Re*pay"</hw> <pr>(r?-p?")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Repaid</conjf> <pr>(-p?d")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Repaying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>re-</ets> +
<ets>pay</ets>: cf. F. <ets>repayer</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
pay back; to refund; <as>as, to <ex>repay</ex> money borrowed or
advanced</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If you <qex>repay</qex> me not on such a day,⟦br⟧
In such a place, such sum or sums.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make return or requital for; to recompense; -- in
a good or bad sense; <as>as, to <ex>repay</ex> kindness; to
<ex>repay</ex> an injury.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Benefits which can not be <qex>repaid</qex> . . . are not commonly
found to increase affection.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pay anew, or a second time, as a debt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To refund; restore; return; recompense;
compensate; remunerate; satisfy; reimburse; requite.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Repayable</ent>⟦br⟧
